 Aristocracy of the Market Basket: Self-Service Food Shopping in the New South -- tChapter 13: Making Markets Marxist? The East European Grocery Store from Rationing to Rationality to Rationalizations -- tChapter 14: Tools and Spaces: Food and Cooking in Working-Class Neighborhoods, 1880–1930 -- tChapter 15: Wheeling One’s Groceries around the Store: The Invention of the Shopping Cart, 1936–1953 -- tNotes -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, the integrity of food production and distribution has become an issue of wide social concern. The media frequently report on cases of food contamination as well as on the risks of hormones and cloning. Journalists, documentary filmmakers, and activists have had their say, but until now a survey of the latest research on the history of the modern food-provisioning system—the network that connects farms and fields to supermarkets and the dining table—has been unavailable. In Food Chains, Warren Belasco and Roger Horowitz present a collection of fascinating case studies that reveal the historical underpinnings and institutional arrangements that compose this system.The dozen essays in Food Chains range widely in subject, from the pig, poultry, and seafood industries to the origins of the shopping cart. The book examines what it took to put ice in nineteenth-century refrigerators, why Soviet citizens could buy ice cream whenever they wanted, what made Mexican food popular in France, and why Americans turned to commercial pet food in place of table scraps for their dogs and cats. Food Chains goes behind the grocery shelves, explaining why Americans in the early twentieth century preferred to buy bread rather than make it and how Southerners learned to like self-serve shopping. Taken together, these essays demonstrate the value of a historical perspective on the modern food-provisioning system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConsumers' preferences. 0aFood consumption. 0aFood industry and trade. 0aFood supply. 0aFoodxMarketing. 4aAmerican History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Agribusiness.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aBusiness.  aEconomics.  aHistory.1 aAnderson, J. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelasco, Warren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelasco, Warren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeltault, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodley, Andrew C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrandclément, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrier, Katherine C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHyder Patterson, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeigh Smith, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPilcher, Jeffrey M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRees, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTolbert, Lisa C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Katherine Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilk, Richard R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTi